*Assessment*

This issue was discovered while testing to see if account-level 'Deny' effect policies were accepted. The odd behavior shows up when one applies a quota policy to a group.

In short, when a policy is added to a group, and resources are created (i.e. instances launched, security groups created, keypairs created, etc.), then the policy is removed and replaced on the group, the non-admin user is not able to see the instances they launched before.  They are, however, able to see the keypairs, security group rules, etc. that they created before.

*Signs*

* Policies applied at account level and group level:
{code}
[root@odc-c-06 ~]# euare-accountlistpolicies -a account4 --region eucalyptus-admin@ -v
ec2-deny-vmtypes
{
  "Version":"2011-04-01",
  "Statement":[
   {
    "Effect":"Deny",
    "Action":"ec2:RunInstances",
    "Resource": [
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.large",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.xlarge"
    ]
  }
  ]
}

[root@odc-c-06 ~]# euare-grouplistpolicies -g user31 --region account4-admin@ -v
ec2-limited-actions
{
  "Version":"2011-04-01",
  "Statement":[
   {
    "Effect":"Allow",
    "Action":"ec2:*",
    "Resource": "*"
  },
  {
   "Effect":"Limit",
   "Action":"ec2:RunInstances",
   "Resource": [
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.medium"
   ],
   "Condition":{
     "NumericLessThanEquals":{
       "ec2:quota-vminstancenumber":"2"
     }
    }
   },
  ]
}
{code}
* Keypairs and Security group rules created:
{code}
[root@odc-c-06 ~]# euca-describe-keypairs --region account4-user31@
